Named after French naval architect <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henri_Dupuy_de_L%c3%b4me" rel="nofollow">Stanislas Charles Henri Dupuy de Lôme (15 October 1816 – 1 February 1885)</a>. 

Not sure if it's this one or a later airship named in honor of Dupuy de Lôme:
&quot;The Dupuy de Lôme airship was 36 meters in length, 14.84 meters in diameter, 29 meters wide, and had a total volume of 3,454 cubic meters. It was powered by a 2 horsepower (1.5 kW) engine, providing a speed of between 9 to 11 km/h. The basket under the balloon could carry eight, several operating the balloon and others observing. She was the first operational airship, and was employed during the last days of the Franco-Prussian war.&quot;
